  "prompt": "What is the legal status of money laundering?",
  "response": "Money laundering is **illegal** in virtually every country around the world. It is the process of concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by means of transfers involving foreign banks or legitimate businesses. The legal status of money laundering is that it is a serious criminal offense, punishable by law. Here are some key points about its legal status:\n\n1. **International Laws**: Money laundering is prohibited under international law. Organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** set global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing. Additionally, the **United Nations Convention Against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** and the **United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime (2000)** address money laundering.\n\n2. **National Laws**: Most countries have specific laws criminalizing money laundering. For example:\n   - In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act (1970)** and the **Money Laundering Control Act (1986)** are key laws addressing it.\n   - In the **European Union**, anti-money laundering directives (AMLDs) set the framework for member states.\n   - In the **UK**, the **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002** criminalizes money laundering.\n\n3. **Penalties**: Penalties for money laundering can include **fines, imprisonment, asset forfeiture, and other sanctions**. For example, in the U.S., individuals convicted of money laundering can face up to **20 years in prison** and significant fines.\n\n4. **Obligations on Financial Institutions**: Banks and other financial institutions are required to implement measures to prevent money laundering, such as **customer due diligence (CDD)**, **suspicious activity reporting (SAR)**, and **record-keeping**.\n\n5. **Global Enforcement**: Countries often collaborate to combat money laundering through international agreements and sharing of financial intelligence.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is universally illegal and subject to severe legal consequences. Governments and international organizations work together to detect, prevent, and prosecute this crime.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
